Impulse
We sometimes encounter examples where a large force acts for a very short duration producing a finite change in momentum of the body.", "fibs": ["F"]}
{"text": "For example, when a ball hits a wall and bounces back, the force on the ball by the wall acts for a very short time when the two are in contact, yet the force is large enough to reverse the momentum of the ball.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Often, in these situations, the force and the time duration are difficult to ascertain separately.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "However, the product of force and time, which is the change in momentum of the body remains a measurable quantity.", "fibs": ["product"]}
{"text": "This product is called impulse:
	Impulse  =  Force × time duration  
     =  Change in momentum                                                                                         (5.7)
A large force acting for a short time to produce a finite change in momentum is called an impulsive force.", "fibs": ["product"]}
{"text": "In the history of science, impulsive forces were put in a conceptually different category from ordinary forces.", "fibs": ["history"]}
{"text": "Newtonian mechanics has no such distinction.", "fibs": ["distinction"]}
{"text": "Impulsive force is like any other force – except that it is large and acts for a short time.", "fibs": ["force"]}
