{"text": "5.9  Common forces in mechanics
In mechanics, we encounter several kinds of forces.", "fibs": ["encounter"]}
{"text": "The gravitational force is, of course, pervasive.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Every object on the earth experiences the force of gravity due to the earth.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "Gravity also governs the motion of celestial bodies.", "fibs": ["Gravity"]}
{"text": "The gravitational force can act at a distance without the need of any intervening medium.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "All the other forces common in mechanics are contact forces.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "* As the name suggests, a contact force on an object arises due to contact with some other object: solid or fluid.", "fibs": ["name"]}
{"text": "When bodies are in contact (e.g.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "a book resting on a table, a system of rigid bodies connected by rods, hinges and other types of supports), there are mutual contact forces (for each pair of bodies) satisfying the third law.", "fibs": ["book"]}
{"text": "The component of contact force normal to the surfaces in contact is called  normal reaction.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "The component parallel to the surfaces in contact is called friction.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "Contact forces arise also when solids are in contact with fluids.", "fibs": ["Contact"]}
{"text": "For example, for a solid immersed in a fluid, there is an upward bouyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The viscous force, air resistance, etc are also examples of contact forces (Fig.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.9 Some examples of contact forces in mechanics.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "* We are not considering, for simplicity, charged and magnetic bodies.", "fibs": ["simplicity"]}
{"text": "For these, besides gravity, there are electrical and magnetic non-contact forces.", "fibs": ["gravity"]}
{"text": "Two other common forces are tension in a string and the force due to spring.", "fibs": ["tension"]}
{"text": "When a spring is compressed or extended by an external force, a restoring force is generated.", "fibs": ["spring"]}
{"text": "This force is usually proportional to the compression or elongation (for small displacements).", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "The spring force F is written as F = – k x where x is the displacement and k is the force constant.", "fibs": ["spring"]}
{"text": "The negative sign denotes that the force is opposite to the displacement from the unstretched state.", "fibs": ["sign"]}
{"text": "For an inextensible string, the force constant is very high.", "fibs": ["string"]}
{"text": "The restoring force in a string is called tension.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "It is customary to use a constant tension T throughout the string.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "This assumption is true for a string of negligible mass.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "In Chapter 1, we learnt that there are four fundamental forces in nature.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "Of these, the weak and strong forces appear in domains that do not concern us here.", "fibs": ["concern"]}
{"text": "Only the gravitational and electrical forces are relevant in the context of mechanics.", "fibs": ["context"]}
{"text": "The different contact forces of mechanics mentioned above fundamentally arise from electrical forces.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "At the microscopic level, all bodies are made of charged constituents (nuclei and electrons) and the various contact forces arising due to elasticity of bodies, molecular collisions and impacts, etc.", "fibs": ["level"]}
{"text": "The detailed microscopic origin of these forces is, however, complex and not useful for handling problems in mechanics at the macroscopic scale.", "fibs": ["origin"]}
{"text": "5.9.1  Friction
Let us return to the example of a body of mass m at rest on a horizontal table.", "fibs": ["return"]}
{"text": "The force of gravity (mg)  is cancelled by the normal reaction force (N) of the table.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Now suppose a force F is applied horizontally to the body.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "We know from experience that a small  applied force may not be enough to move the body.", "fibs": ["experience"]}
{"text": "But if the applied force F were the only external force on the body, it must move with acceleration F/m, however small.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Clearly, the body remains at rest because some other force comes into play in the horizontal direction and opposes the applied force F, resulting in zero net force on the body.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "This force fs parallel to the surface of the body in contact with the table is known as frictional force, or simply friction (Fig.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "5.10(a)).", "fibs": ["5.10(a"]}
{"text": "The subscript stands for static friction to distinguish it from kinetic friction fk that we consider later (Fig.", "fibs": ["subscript"]}
{"text": "5.10(b)).", "fibs": ["5.10(b"]}
{"text": "Note that  static friction does not exist by itself.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "When there is no applied force, there is no static friction.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "It comes into play the moment there is an applied force.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "As the applied force F increases, fs also increases, remaining equal and opposite to the applied force (up to a certain limit), keeping the body at rest.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Hence, it is called static friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "Static friction opposes impending motion.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "The term impending motion means motion that would take place (but does not actually take place) under the applied force, if friction were absent.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.10 Static and sliding friction: (a)  Impending motion of the body is opposed by static friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "When external force exceeds the maximum limit of static friction, the body begins to move.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "(b) Once the body is in motion, it is subject to sliding or kinetic friction which opposes relative motion between the two surfaces in contact.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Kinetic friction is usually less than the maximum value of static friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "We know from experience that as the applied force exceeds a certain limit, the body begins to move.", "fibs": ["experience"]}
