{"text": "For a body moving with  constant velocity, F = fk.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "If the applied force on the body is removed, its acceleration is – fk /m  and it eventually comes to a stop.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "The laws of friction given above do not have the status of fundamental laws like those for gravitational, electric and magnetic forces.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "Thus, when two bodies are in contact, each experiences a contact force by the other.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "Friction, by definition, is the component of the contact force parallel to the surfaces in contact, which opposes impending or actual relative motion between the two surfaces.", "fibs": ["Friction"]}
{"text": "Note that it is not motion, but relative motion that the frictional force opposes.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Consider a box lying in the compartment of a train that is accelerating.", "fibs": ["box"]}
{"text": "If the box is stationary relative to the train, it is in fact accelerating along with the train.", "fibs": ["box"]}
{"text": "What forces cause the acceleration of the box?", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "Clearly, the only conceivable force in the horizontal direction is the force of friction.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "If there were no friction, the floor of the train would slip by and the box would remain at its initial position due to inertia (and hit the back side of the train).", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "This impending relative motion is opposed by the static friction fs.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Static friction provides the same acceleration to the box as that of the train, keeping it stationary relative to the train.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
