Rolling friction
A body like a ring or a sphere rolling without slipping over a horizontal plane will suffer no friction, in principle.", "fibs": ["–2"]}
{"text": "At every instant, there is just one point of contact between the body and the plane and this point has no motion relative to the plane.", "fibs": ["instant"]}
{"text": "In this ideal situation, kinetic or static friction is zero and the body should continue to roll with constant velocity.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "We know, in practice, this will not happen and some resistance to motion (rolling friction) does occur, i.e.", "fibs": ["practice"]}
{"text": "to keep the body rolling, some applied force is needed.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "For the same weight, rolling friction is much smaller (even by 2 or 3 orders of magnitude) than static or sliding friction.", "fibs": ["weight"]}
{"text": "This is the reason why discovery of the wheel has been a major milestone in human history.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "Rolling friction again has a complex origin, though somewhat different from that of static and sliding friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "During rolling, the surfaces in contact get momentarily deformed a little, and this results in a finite area (not a point) of the body being in contact with the surface.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "The net effect is that the component of the contact force parallel to the surface opposes motion.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "We often regard friction as something undesirable.", "fibs": ["regard"]}
{"text": "In many situations, like in a machine with different moving parts, friction does have a negative role.", "fibs": ["machine"]}
{"text": "It opposes relative motion and thereby dissipates power in the form of heat, etc.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Lubricants are a way of reducing kinetic friction in a machine.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "Another way is to use ball bearings between two moving parts of a machine [Fig.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "5.13(a)].", "fibs": ["5.13(a"]}
{"text": "Since the rolling friction between ball bearings and the surfaces in contact is very small, power dissipation is reduced.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "A thin cushion of air maintained between solid surfaces in relative motion is another effective way of reducing friction (Fig.", "fibs": ["cushion"]}
{"text": "5.13(a)).", "fibs": ["5.13(a"]}
{"text": "In many practical situations, however, friction is critically needed.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "Kinetic friction that dissipates power is nevertheless important for quickly stopping relative motion.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "It is made use of by brakes in machines and automobiles.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Similarly, static friction is important in daily life.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "We are able to walk because of friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "It is impossible for a car to move on a very slippery road.", "fibs": ["car"]}
{"text": "On an ordinary road, the friction between the tyres and the road provides the necessary external force to accelerate the car.", "fibs": ["road"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.13 Some ways of reducing friction.", "fibs": ["friction"]}
{"text": "(a) Ball bearings placed between moving parts of a machine.", "fibs": ["machine"]}
{"text": "(b) Compressed cushion of air between surfaces in relative motion.", "fibs": ["b"]}
