{"text": "Action-reaction pairs
For (a):	(i) the force of gravity (20 N) on the block by the earth (say, action); the force of gravity on the earth by the block (reaction) equal to 20 N directed upwards (not shown in the figure).", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "(ii) the force on the floor by the block (action); the force on the block by the floor (reaction).", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "For (b):	(i) the force of gravity (270 N) on the system by the earth (say, action); the force of gravity on the earth by the system (reaction), equal to 270 N, directed upwards (not shown in the figure).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "(ii) the force on the floor by the system (action); the force on the system by the  floor (reaction).", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "In addition, for (b), the force on the block by the cylinder and the force on the cylinder by the block also constitute an action-reaction pair.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "The important thing to remember is that an action-reaction pair consists of mutual forces  which are always equal and opposite between two bodies.", "fibs": ["thing"]}
{"text": "Two forces on the same body which happen to be equal and opposite can never constitute an action-reaction pair.", "fibs": ["body"]}
{"text": "The force of gravity on the mass in (a) or (b) and the normal force on the mass by the floor are not action-reaction pairs.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "These forces happen to be equal and opposite for (a) since the mass is at rest.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "They are not so for case (b), as seen already.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The weight of the system is 270 N, while the normal force R′ is 267.3 N. 
	The practice of drawing free-body diagrams is of great help in solving problems in mechanics.", "fibs": ["weight"]}
{"text": "It allows you to clearly define your system and consider all forces on the system due to objects that are not part of the system itself.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "A number of exercises in this and subsequent chapters will help you cultivate this practice.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Aristotle’s view that a force is necessary to keep a body in uniform motion is wrong.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "A force is necessary in practice to counter the opposing force of friction.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Galileo extrapolated simple observations on motion of bodies on inclined planes, and arrived at the law of inertia.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Newton’s first law of motion is the same law rephrased thus: “Everybody continues to be in its state of rest or of uniform motion in a straight line, unless compelled by some external force to act otherwise”.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "In simple terms, the First Law is “If external force on a body is zero, its acceleration is zero”.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Momentum (p ) of a body is the product of its mass (m) and velocity (v) :
 p  =  m v
4.", "fibs": ["Momentum"]}
{"text": "Newton’s second law of motion :
 The rate of change of momentum of a body is proportional to the applied force and takes place in the direction in which the force acts.", "fibs": ["’"]}
